To assess the utility of the established assays in real serum samples, different concentration of miRNA-222 was added in a 1000−fold diluted normal human serum, and then ECL measurement was repeated for 3 times, respectively. As depicted in Table 1
                        , the resultant recoveries of the developed biosensor were 88.2–105.9% and RSD was in the range of 2.5–4.29%, manifesting its strong anti-interference ability and potential for miRNA-222 determination in real serum samples. Further, compared with other detection methods toward miRNA-222 (Table 2
                        ), this ECL biosensor exhibited relatively low detection limit and wide linear range, suggesting its prospect in disease-related biomarker determination.
